# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/air-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] An **automotive battery**, or **car battery**, is a rechargeable battery that is used to start a motor vehicle, and to power lights, screen wiper etc. while the engine is off.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Its main purpose is to provide an electric current to the electric-powered starting motor, which in turn starts the chemically-powered internal combustion engine that actually propels the vehicle.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Once the engine is running, power for the car's electrical systems is still supplied by the battery, with the alternator charging the battery as demands increase or decrease.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Typically, starting uses less than three percent of the battery capacity.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] For this reason, automotive batteries are designed to deliver maximum current for a short period of time.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] They are sometimes referred to as "SLI batteries" for this reason, for starting, lighting and ignition.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] SLI batteries are not designed for deep discharging, and a full discharge can reduce the battery's lifespan.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] As well as starting the engine, an SLI battery supplies the extra power necessary when the vehicle's electrical requirements exceed the supply from the charging system.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] It is also a stabilizer, evening out potentially damaging voltage spikes.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] While the engine is running most of the power is provided by the alternator (or in older vehicles a generator or dynamo), which includes a voltage regulator to keep the output between 13.5 and 14.5 V.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Modern SLI batteries are lead-acid type, using six series-connected cells to provide a nominal 12-volt system (in most passenger vehicles and light trucks), or twelve cells for a 24-volt system in heavy trucks or earth-moving equipment, for example.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Gas explosions can occur at the negative electrode where hydrogen gas can build up due to blocked battery vents or a poorly ventilated setting, combined with an ignition source.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Explosions during engine start-up are typically associated with corroded or dirty battery posts.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] A 1993 study by the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said that 31% of vehicle battery explosion injuries occurred while charging the battery.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Close to two-thirds of those injured suffered chemical burns, and nearly three-fourths suffered eye injuries, among other possible injuries.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Electric vehicles (EVs) are powered by a high-voltage electric vehicle battery, but they usually have an automotive battery as well, so that they can use standard automotive accessories which are designed to run on 12 V.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Unlike conventional, internal combustion engined vehicles, EVs don't charge the auxiliary battery with an alternator—instead, they use a DC-to-DC converter to step down the high voltage to the required float-charge voltage (typically around 14 V).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Further, an electric vehicle does not have a starter motor, thus needs only a limited amount of power and energy from its auxiliary battery.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] As such, Tesla introduced in 2021 a lithium-ion auxiliary battery storing only 99 Wh of energy.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Early cars did not have batteries, as their electrical systems were limited.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Electric power for the ignition was provided by a magneto, the engine was started with a crank, headlights were gas-powered and a bell or bulb-horn was used instead of an electric horn.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Car batteries became widely used around 1920 as cars became equipped with electric starter motors.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The first starting and charging systems were designed to be 6-volt and positive-ground systems, with the vehicle's chassis directly connected to the positive battery terminal.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Today, almost all road vehicles have a negative ground system.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The negative battery terminal is connected to the car's chassis.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The Hudson Motor Car Company was the first to use a standardized battery in 1918 when they started using Battery Council International batteries.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] BCI is the organization that sets the dimensional standards for batteries.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Cars used 6 V electrical systems and batteries until the mid-1950s.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The changeover from 6 to 12 V happened when bigger engines with higher compression ratios required more electrical power to start.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Smaller cars, which required less power to start stayed with 6 V longer, for example the Volkswagen Beetle in the mid-1960s and the Citroën 2CV in 1970.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The AGM sealed battery (for automobiles), which did not require refilling, was invented in 1971.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] In the 1990s a 42V electrical system standard was proposed.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] It was intended to allow more powerful electrically driven accessories, and lighter automobile wiring harnesses.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] However, the availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques, and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators have largely eliminated the push for switching the main automotive voltages.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] In 2023 Tesla started deliveries of their Cybertruck that uses a 48-volt electrical system, reducing 70% of the wiring in the vehicle.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] An automobile battery is an example of a wet cell battery, with six cells.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Each cell of a lead storage battery consists of alternate plates made of a lead alloy grid filled with sponge lead plates (cathode) or coated with lead dioxide (anode).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Each cell is filled with a sulfuric acid solution, which is the electrolyte.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Initially, cells each had a filler cap, through which the electrolyte level could be viewed and which allowed water to be added to the cell.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The filler cap had a small vent hole which allowed hydrogen gas generated during charging to escape from the cell.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The cells are connected by short heavy straps from the positive plates of one cell to the negative plates of the adjacent cell.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] A pair of heavy terminals, plated with lead to resist corrosion, are mounted at the top, sometimes the side, of the battery.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Early auto batteries used hard rubber cases and wooden plate separators.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Modern units use plastic cases and woven sheets to prevent the plates of a cell from touching and short-circuiting.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] In the past, auto batteries required regular inspection and maintenance to replace water that was decomposed during the operation of the battery.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] "Low-maintenance" (sometimes called "zero-maintenance") batteries use a different alloy for the plate elements, reducing the amount of water decomposed on charging.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] A modern battery may not require additional water over its useful life; some types eliminate the individual filler caps for each cell.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] A weakness of these batteries is that they are very intolerant of deep discharge, such as when the car battery is completely drained by leaving the lights on.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] This coats the lead plate electrodes with lead sulfate deposits and can reduce the battery's lifespan by a third or more.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries, also known as absorbed glass mat (AGM) batteries are more tolerant of deep discharge but are more expensive.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries do not permit addition of water to the cell.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The cells each have an automatic pressure release valve, to protect the case from rupture on severe overcharge or internal failure.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] A VRLA battery cannot spill its electrolyte which makes it particularly useful in vehicles such as motorcycles.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Batteries are typically made of six galvanic cells in a series circuits.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Each cell provides 2.1 volts for a total of 12.6 volts at full charge.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] During discharge, at the negative (lead) terminal a chemical reaction releases electrons to the external circuit, and at the positive (lead oxide) terminal another chemical reaction absorbs electrons from the external circuit.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] This drives the electrons through the external circuit wire (an electrical conductor) to produce an electric current (electricity).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] As the battery discharges, the acid of the electrolyte reacts with the materials of the plates, changing their surface to lead sulfate.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] When the battery is recharged, the chemical reaction is reversed: the lead sulfate reforms into lead dioxide.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] With the plates restored to their original condition, the process may be repeated.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Some vehicles use other starter batteries.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] For weight savings, the 2010 Porsche 911 GT3 RS has a lithium-ion battery as an option; from 2018 onward, all Kia Niro conventional hybrids feature one as well.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Heavy vehicles may have two batteries in series for a 24 V system or may have series-parallel groups of batteries supplying 24 V.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Batteries are grouped by physical size, type and placement of the terminals, and mounting style.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Battery Council International (BCI) group size specifies a battery's physical dimensions, such as length, width, and height.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] These groups are determined by the organization.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Ampere hours (Ah or A·h) is a unit related to the energy storage capacity of the battery.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] This rating is required by law in Europe.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The ampere hour rating represents the total current delivered over a period of 20 hours before voltage drops below 10.5 volts while operating at a temperature of 80 °F (26.6 °C).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] In theory, at 80 °F, a 100 Ah battery should be able to continuously provide 5 amps for 20 hours while maintaining a voltage of at least 10.5 volts.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The relationship between the Ah capacity and the discharge rate is not linear; as the discharge rate is increased, the capacity decreases.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] A battery with a 100 Ah rating generally will not be able to maintain a voltage above 10.5 volts for 10 hours while being discharged at constant rate of 10 amps.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Capacity also decreases with temperature.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Excess heat is a main cause of battery failures, as when the electrolyte evaporates due to high temperatures, decreasing the effective surface area of the plates exposed to the electrolyte, and leading to sulfation.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Grid corrosion rates increase with temperature.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Also low temperatures can lead to battery failure.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] If the battery is discharged to the point where it can't start the engine, the engine can be jump started via an external source of power.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Once running, the engine can recharge the battery, if the alternator and charging system are undamaged.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Corrosion at the battery terminals can prevent a car from starting due to electrical resistance, which can be prevented by the proper application of dielectric grease.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Sulfation is when the electrodes become coated with a hard layer of lead sulfate, which weakens the battery.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Sulfation can happen when battery is not fully charged and remains discharged.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Sulfated batteries should be charged slowly to prevent damage.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] SLI batteries (starting, lighting, and ignition) are not designed for deep discharge, and their life is reduced when subjected to this.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Starting batteries have plates designed for increased surface area and thus high instant current capability, whereas marine (hybrid) and deep cycle types will have thicker plates and more room at the bottom of the plates for spent plate material to gather before shorting the cell.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Car batteries using lead-antimony plates require regular topping-up with pure water to replace water lost due to electrolysis and evaporation.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] By changing the alloying element to calcium, more recent designs have reduced the rate of water loss.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Modern car batteries have reduced maintenance requirements, and may not provide caps for addition of water to the cells.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Such batteries include extra electrolyte above the plates to allow for losses during the battery life.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Some battery manufacturers include a built-in hydrometer to show the state of charge of the battery.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The primary wear-out mechanism is the shedding of active material from the battery plates, which accumulates at the bottom of the cells and which may eventually short-circuit the plates.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] This can be substantially reduced by enclosing one set of plates in plastic separator bags, made from a permeable material.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] This allows the electrolyte and ions to pass through but keeps the sludge build up from bridging the plates.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The sludge largely consists of lead sulfate, which is produced at both electrodes.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Battery recycling of automotive batteries reduces the need for resources required for the manufacture of new batteries, diverts toxic lead from landfills, and prevents the risk of improper disposal.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Once a lead–acid battery ceases to hold a charge, it is deemed a used lead-acid battery (ULAB), which is classified as hazardous waste under the Basel Convention.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] The 12-volt car battery is the most recycled product in the world, according to the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] In the U.S. alone, about 130 million auto batteries a year are replaced, and 99 percent of them are turned in for recycling.[1] However, the recycling may be done incorrectly in unregulated environments.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] As part of global waste trade, ULABs are shipped from industrialized countries to developing countries for disassembly and recuperation of the contents.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] About 97 percent of the lead can be recovered.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Pure Earth estimates that over 12 million people in developing countries are affected by lead contamination from ULAB processing.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] ULAB recycling has been used as an example supporting the pollution haven hypothesis.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/automotive-battery] Following this change, American exports of used lead-acid batteries to Mexico increased four-fold, which was followed by a significant increase in babies born with low birth weight to mothers living within a two-mile (3.2 km) radius of Mexican battery-recycling plants.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] An **exhaust gas temperature gauge** (**EGT gauge** or **EGT sensor**) is a meter used to monitor the exhaust gas temperature of an internal combustion engine in conjunction with a thermocouple-type pyrometer.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] EGT gauges are found in certain cars and aircraft.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] By monitoring EGT, the driver or pilot can get an idea of the vehicle's air-fuel ratio (AFR).
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] At a stoichiometric air-fuel ratio, the exhaust gas temperature is different from that in a lean or rich air-fuel ratio.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] At rich air-fuel ratio, the exhaust gas temperature either increases or decreases depending on the fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] High temperatures (typically above 1,600 °F or 900 °C) can be an indicator of dangerous conditions that can lead to catastrophic engine failure.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] Using an EGT meter alone is considered an older technique for getting the most out of petrol and diesel engines, as gauge-type wideband digital oxygen sensors are similarly priced.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] However, some advanced racers will use EGT gauges in combination with a wideband oxygen sensor to lean the fuel ratio a bit to safely raise the temperature for more power.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] Though by tuning primarily by EGT and air fuel ratio values, EGT is still to this day a used data output for engine tuning.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] When fine tuning an engine, if possible with the ECU manipulation with the cylinder's timing can be made.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] By adjusting the timing, the resultant cylinder temperature can be used to improve cylinder efficiency.
[src:exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge/exhaust-gas-temperature-gauge] Though this is still widely done, EGT values should be used as a safe guard sensor measure and as a tuning guide.
